Anonymous Fri 25 May 2018 21:05:28 No.15990257 Report
Quoted By: >>15990588
>>15988999
You're not wrong about brevity, but limiting the word count you're willing to face is a pretty suboptimal way to find it. Functionally, brevity has more to do with density than outright length. It is very possible to write a good, long book. "Brief" can stretch a long fucking way if the thing you're addressing is big enough, and it's equally possible to write a technically short but hardly brief story.

In example, your text limit would allow you to read Scarlett Letter, which features some of the least effective language I've ever read in a classic, but prevent you from reading Grapes of Wrath, which is a hell of a lot more direct on a word-for-word basis. It would also nearly allow you to read 20,000 Leagues Under the Sea, which reads like a goddamn fanfic and eats up a 100,000 words with passive language and pretty much no imagery whatsoever. Brevity has a lot more to do with the use of language than the amount of it; it's only half of the length equation.

>Find a story over 100k
Pretty sure NoF and Hel are the only ones that are. AtR might be. I'd agree that NoF is overdense, especially in the beginning, but I wouldn't call it bad.
